TOUPPER(3)                 Linux Programmer's Manual                TOUPPER(3)

NNAAMMEE
       toupper, tolower, toupper_l, tolower_l - convert uppercase or lowercase

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ##iinncclluuddee <<ccttyyppee..hh>>

       iinntt ttoouuppppeerr((iinntt _c));;
       iinntt ttoolloowweerr((iinntt _c));;

       iinntt ttoouuppppeerr__ll((iinntt _c,, llooccaallee__tt _l_o_c_a_l_e));;
       iinntt ttoolloowweerr__ll((iinntt _c,, llooccaallee__tt _l_o_c_a_l_e));;

   Feature Test Macro Requirements for glibc (see ffeeaattuurree__tteesstt__mmaaccrrooss(7)):

       ttoouuppppeerr__ll(), ttoolloowweerr__ll():
           Since glibc 2.10:
                  _XOPEN_SOURCE >= 700
           Before glibc 2.10:
                  _GNU_SOURCE

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       These functions convert lowercase letters to uppercase, and vice versa.

       If _c is a lowercase letter, ttoouuppppeerr() returns its uppercase equivalent,
       if an uppercase representation exists in the  current  locale.   Other‐
       wise,  it  returns _c.  The ttoouuppppeerr__ll() function performs the same task,
       but uses the locale referred to by the locale handle _l_o_c_a_l_e.

       If _c is a uppercase letter, ttoolloowweerr() returns its lowercase equivalent,
       if a lowercase representation exists in the current locale.  Otherwise,
       it returns _c.  The ttoolloowweerr__ll() function performs  the  same  task,  but
       uses the locale referred to by the locale handle _l_o_c_a_l_e.

       If  _c  is neither an _u_n_s_i_g_n_e_d _c_h_a_r value nor EEOOFF, the behavior of these
       functions is undefined.

       The behavior of ttoouuppppeerr__ll() and ttoolloowweerr__ll() is undefined if  _l_o_c_a_l_e  is
       the special locale object LLCC__GGLLOOBBAALL__LLOOCCAALLEE (see dduuppllooccaallee(3)) or is not
       a valid locale object handle.

RREETTUURRNN VVAALLUUEE
       The value returned is that of the converted letter, or _c if the conver‐
       sion was not possible.

AATTTTRRIIBBUUTTEESS
       For   an   explanation   of   the  terms  used  in  this  section,  see
       aattttrriibbuutteess(7).

       ┌─────────────────────────┬───────────────┬─────────┐
       │IInntteerrffaaccee                │ AAttttrriibbuuttee     │ VVaalluuee   │
       ├─────────────────────────┼───────────────┼─────────┤
       │ttoouuppppeerr(), ttoolloowweerr(),    │ Thread safety │ MT-Safe │
       │ttoouuppppeerr__ll(), ttoolloowweerr__ll() │               │         │
       └─────────────────────────┴───────────────┴─────────┘
CCOONNFFOORRMMIINNGG TTOO
       ttoouuppppeerr(), ttoolloowweerr(): C89, C99, 4.3BSD, POSIX.1-2001, POSIX.1-2008.

       ttoouuppppeerr__ll(), ttoolloowweerr__ll(): POSIX.1-2008.

NNOOTTEESS
       The details of what constitutes an uppercase or lowercase letter depend
       on the locale.  For example, the default ""CC"" locale does not know about
       umlauts, so no conversion is done for them.

       In some non-English locales, there are lowercase letters with no corre‐
       sponding uppercase equivalent; the German sharp s is one example.

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       iissaallpphhaa(3),   nneewwllooccaallee(3),  sseettllooccaallee(3),  uusseellooccaallee(3),  ttoowwlloowweerr(3),
       ttoowwuuppppeerr(3), llooccaallee(7)

